# org-config.md template (session-handoff v0.1.0, schema 0.1)

This file is a **template**. The session-handoff skill renders it into your project space as `config/org-config.md` (or `config-org-config.md` on flat surfaces) on first invocation if you do not already have one. Your organization then populates the `[tbd]` placeholders.

To configure interactively, load the rendered file and tell your AI "walk me through configuring this." It runs the shared interview (`references/configure.md`), uses the FIELD GUIDE below, and writes a new version for approval before saving. Changes touching governance fields are flagged as compliance-relevant in the approval summary.

Resolution order at runtime: `config/user-config.md` > `config/org-config.md` > skill defaults in `references/defaults.md`. For consolidated handoffs, most-restrictive governance derivation from the sources takes precedence (`references/lineage.md` section 4).

org-config holds the compliance taxonomy configured once; `config/redaction-policy.md` holds the redaction rules that key off this taxonomy. They layer; they do not duplicate. This org-config is also intended to be honored by the sister skill project-context, so an organization configures compliance once across both skills.

The rendered file is the content inside the fenced block below: everything from the `---` frontmatter through the final config key. On first run the skill auto-extracts exactly that fenced block (not this SPDX header or surrounding prose) and writes it as `config/org-config.md`. To do it by hand, copy everything inside the fence into `config/org-config.md` and fill the `[tbd]` fields:

```yaml
---
schema_version: "0.1"
_managed_by: session-handoff-skill
config_type: org
config_editable: true
configure_with: references/configure.md
---
# To configure: load this file and tell your AI "walk me through configuring this."
# It runs the shared interview (references/configure.md), uses the FIELD GUIDE below,
# and writes a new version of this file for approval before saving.
#
# ============================================================
# session-handoff - org configuration (v0.1.0, schema 0.1)
# ============================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: org
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Organization identity stamped where the skill records org
# scope.
#
# name (REQUIRED): the organization name.
# type: free-form, e.g. "public-company", "private", "agency".
# tenant: an optional tenant or workspace identifier.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
org:
  name: "[tbd]"
  type: "[tbd]"
  tenant: null


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: compliance  (COMPLIANCE-RELEVANT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# The compliance taxonomy, configured once and keyed off by
# the redaction policy. Changes here are flagged as
# compliance-relevant in the configure interview.
#
# default_sensitivity: the org default sensitivity for new
#   handoffs. One of: open | internal | confidential | restricted
# regulatory_scope: frameworks that apply org-wide, stamped
#   into governance_frameworks, e.g. ["SOX","ITAR"].
# sensitivity_levels: the org's sensitivity vocabulary if it
#   differs from the default four; leave as the default unless
#   your org uses different labels.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
compliance:
  default_sensitivity: "internal"
  regulatory_scope: []
  sensitivity_levels: ["open", "internal", "confidential", "restricted"]


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: sanctioned_destinations  (COMPLIANCE-RELEVANT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Sanctioned-destination awareness (governance feature 4). When
# a list is set, pre-flight checks a handoff's stated or detected
# destination against it.
#
# enabled: false leaves the check inert (public default).
# enforcement: "warn" (pre-flight warns) or "block" (pre-flight
#   refuses an unsanctioned destination).
# allowed: the list of sanctioned platforms, tools, or recipients.
#   Empty until your org defines it; the skill never invents one.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
sanctioned_destinations:
  enabled: false
  enforcement: "warn"
  allowed: []


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: governance_overrides
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Org-level overrides of skill defaults.
#
# sanitization_prompt: override the gate org-wide. An enterprise
#   may set "always" for a sanitize prompt on every run.
#   One of: always | on-signal | never
# prior_handoffs_entry_shape: the consolidation ledger entry
#   shape. "id-string" (public default) or "enriched-object"
#   ({ id, kind, sensitivity }) for self-auditing enterprises.
# consolidate_cap_mode: "soft" or "hard".
# consolidate_max_sources: the soft review-batch guardrail.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
governance_overrides:
  sanitization_prompt: "on-signal"
  prior_handoffs_entry_shape: "id-string"
  consolidate_cap_mode: "soft"
  consolidate_max_sources: 3


# -----------------------------------------------------------
# FIELD GUIDE: methodology_hooks
# -----------------------------------------------------------
# Optional org methodology hooks the skill may surface after a
# write (e.g. a downstream capture step). Free-form list of
# short instruction strings; empty by default. Keep these
# descriptive; orchestration stays in the trusted skill.
# -----------------------------------------------------------
methodology_hooks: []
```

## Required fields

- `org.name`

Other fields carry safe defaults. A rendered file with `org.name` still `[tbd]` is permitted but pre-flight notes it.

## What does not belong in org-config.md

- Per-user preferences; those live in `config/user-config.md`.
- The redaction rules themselves; those live in `config/redaction-policy.md`, which keys off the `compliance` taxonomy here.
- Secrets or credentials.

## Cross-skill convention

This org-config is intended to be shared with the sister skill project-context so an organization configures compliance once. See `README.md`.
